                    <lb n="3"/>καὶ οἱ ἀλ<supplied reason="omitted">ειφόμενοι</supplied>
                    <lb n="4"/> Ἡρακλεῖ.
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus" resp="#MH">
                <listApp>
                    <app>
                        <note>Text according to Kaibel in IG</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="2">
                        <note>Torremuzza: ΚΑΙΟΙΑΛΛΟΙΠΟΛΙ</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <p> (---) son of Polyxenos and those who have been annointed (dedicate this) to Herakles</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p><!--commented out pending revision-->
                    <!--curious, b/c apparently by Polyxenos on behalf of all the other citizens, to Heracles, for which few if any parallels. cf. IG 14.369-71 for possible parallels. A better / alternative restoration is that it appears to record a dedication by aleiphomenoi, to Herakles, in which case evidence for a gymnasion. Delorme 1960, p.340 n.4 observes this dedication, in the context of such dedications being common to gymnasia, but also observes that the facsimile of the inscr. (unlike Kaibel’s proposed text) reads kai hoi alloi poli at line 3 rather than hoi aleiphomenoi, and it may have no connection with athletics. Kaibel makes his conjecture (which MHC thinks plausible) on the basis that it’s a bad apograph by Torremuzza, and that it’s highly unlikely to have one citizen making a dedication on behalf of the rest, and one has the parallels of Haluntium for dedications by hoi aleiphomenoi. Cordiano, 1997,  p.89 with n.295 cites this and says that a) ref. to aleiphomenoi is possible and b) granted which, a dedication in a local gymnasium is ‘probable’--></p>
            </div>
